  "prompt": "Why do people hate accounting?",
  "response": "People may dislike accounting for several reasons:\n\n1. Complexity\n- Technical terminology\n- Complex rules and regulations\n- Requires detailed, precise work\n\n2. Perceived Monotony\n- Repetitive tasks\n- Lots of data entry\n- Seems mundane and routine\n\n3. Difficulty\n- Mathematical calculations\n- Challenging concepts\n- Requires strong analytical skills\n\n4. Stress Factors\n- High-pressure environments\n- Strict deadlines\n- Potential consequences of errors\n\n5. Negative Stereotypes\n- Seen as boring profession\n- Viewed as dry and uninteresting\n- Portrayed as uncreative work\n\n6. Mental Demands\n- Requires constant focus\n- Needs high attention to detail\n- Can be mentally exhausting\n\n7. Technical Nature\n- Heavy reliance on technology\n- Constant software updates\n- Requires continuous learning\n\n8. Time-Consuming\n- Long hours during tax season\n- Extensive documentation\n- Requires significant preparation\n\n9. Personal Skills Mismatch\n- Not everyone enjoys number-crunching\n- Doesn't align with creative personalities\n- Different cognitive strengths\n\n10. High Accountability\n- Legal and financial responsibilities\n- Potential personal liability\n- Risk of professional consequences\n\nThese factors contribute to many people's negative perception of accounting.",
